A comment from Dr Steve Berger
------------------------------
The paucity of available clinical data on this outbreak precludes any
meaningful diagnosis; this cluster of fever and severe joint pain is
reminiscent of the current outbreak of Chikungunya in Reunion.
The following background information on Chikungunya in India is abstracted
from the GIDEON database:
Chikungunya is common, and periodic epidemics are reported. Outbreaks have
been described in Madras and Vellore. 2.9 per cent of people living in the
Andaman and Nicobar Islands are seropositive. Infected mosquitoes have been
documented in Pune District (Maharashtra State).
Notable outbreaks include the following:
1963 to 1965 - an outbreak was reported in Calcutta. 4.4 per cent of the
population were later found to be seropositive.
1973 - an outbreak in Barsi (Sholapur district), Maharashtra state involved
37.5 per cent of the population.
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
