Comment from Wojtek Kalman
--------------------------
I'm probably not the only one who will make a similar comment, but I'd like
to draw attention to ProMED-mail posting "Chikungunya - India (AP): susp.
20060220.0551" of 20 Feb 2006, referring to a probable Chikungunya outbreak
in 5 districts of Andhra Pradesh province. It doesn't report more precisely
where (in which districts) the outbreak has been discovered in Andhra
Pradesh, but Karnataka province borders Andhra Pradesh, and Bellary
district, mentioned in the current RFI, is located very close to the border
between both provinces.
--
Wojtek Kalman
Interested lay person
Gdansk, Poland
<wojtek_ka@wp.pl>
[The same suggestion was contributed by Patricia Doyle. ProMED-mail would
welcome verification from a local source that Chikungunya virus (CHIKV) is
indeed the etiologic agent of this outbreak of febrile disease in the
province of Karnataka.
CHIKV is a mosquito-transmitted virus 1st isolated during an epidemic in
Tanzania in 1952/53 from both patients and mosquitoes. Since 1954, it has
been isolated frequently from humans and mosquitoes in tropical Africa, the
India subcontinent, and South East Asia (the Philippines, Thailand,
Cambodia, Viet Nam, Burma, and Sri Lanka). CHIKV is classified in the genus
_Alphavirus_ of the family _Togaviridaae_. It is closely related
phylogenetically to O'nyong-nyong virus (ONNV), and the 2 viruses are
associated with clinically indistinguishable disease, but ONNV has a
restricted distribution in the African continent.
Non-human reservoir species of CHIKV have not been identified
unequivocally. Migrants and travelers have been blamed frequently for
spread of infection; for example, for the comparatively recent introduction
of the disease into Malaysia and the recent (2005-2006) widespread CHIKV
outbreaks around Comoros island.
The largest epidemics of CHIKV infection in recent years have occurred in
India and Indonesia. CHIKV fever is characterized by sudden onset of chills
and fever, headache, nausea, vomiting, arthralgia, and rash. Arthralgia
(the joints of the extremities in particular become swollen and painful to
the touch) is the most typical sign of CHIKV infection, occurring in around
70 per cent of cases. The acute phase of the disease lasts for 2 to 4 days,
with recovery in 5 to 7 days. - Mods.RY/CP]
